Convergence pattern analysis
The curve shows two distinct phases. Rounds 1–22 were fast learning (F1 jumping from 0.27 → 0.80, about +0.025 per round). Rounds 22–35 are a plateau oscillating around 0.80–0.82 with occasional new bests. This is normal FedAvg behaviour: early rounds aggregate large gradient signals, later rounds refine in the presence of competing non-IID gradients. Based on the decay rate, rounds 36–50 should push to roughly 0.85–0.87.
Why it won't reach 0.955 (the paper target)
The paper's result was achieved with a single centralized training run, not FL. The 0.93 gap between your FL best (0.82) and the paper is the sum of three unavoidable penalties: the privacy cost of not sharing raw data, the non-IID data distribution across 12 nodes, and the smaller effective dataset per node. A gap of ~10% F1 is actually considered a good FL result for this level of heterogeneity — it's within the range Li et al. (2020) report for FedProx on non-IID splits.
What to do when training finishes
If the final F1 plateaus below 0.87, there is one more thing to try without touching the architecture: increase --mu slightly to 0.05. The current mu=0.01 is loose enough that clients are still drifting noticeably (you can see it in the oscillation between rounds 22–35 — a round improves, the next regresses). A stronger proximal anchor may smooth the plateau. Run:
python fl_training_BICNNLSTM.py --num_rounds 30 --local_epochs 3 --mu 0.05
starting from scratch — it will converge faster because the model already knows the right regime from your current run's observations, and 30 rounds is enough to reach the plateau with mu=0.05.
