What the data tells us
Phase 1 — fast learning (rounds 1–22). F1 rockets from 0.27 to 0.80 in 22 rounds, roughly +0.025 per round. This is gradient signal from all 7 attack classes finally reaching the global model thanks to the fixed balanced partition.
Phase 2 — oscillating plateau (rounds 22–50). F1 bounces between 0.79–0.83 with occasional spikes (R28: 0.806, R30: 0.819, R44: 0.834). The plateau is not caused by the model hitting a capacity ceiling — it's caused by competing non-IID gradients being averaged at a learning rate that is now too high for the fine-tuning phase. Notice that client accuracy keeps climbing to 95% while server Macro F1 stays at 83%. That 12-point divergence is the signature problem: clients are overfitting to their local 4-class distributions, and the Adam optimizer restarts fresh every round with lr=1e-3 — the same aggressive rate used in round 1.
The RF gap. RF Macro F1 is 0.932. Your best FL is 0.834. The remaining 9.86% gap after all the fixes is now explained by three things: (1) learning rate decay (FL uses a fixed lr=1e-3 for all 50 rounds, while the task needs a lower rate in the plateau phase), (2) the optimizer state is discarded between rounds (each client starts Adam from scratch every round, throwing away momentum), and (3) recon has low recall even in RF (0.873) which suggests the 17 features themselves have limited separability for this class.